  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Conditions for Perpendicularity and  Parallelism ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Angle between two straight lines&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>for two lines ${{l}_{1}}\\And {{l}_{2}}$, the angle between them is given by the formula</p><p>$\\text{tan}\\theta =\\left| \\frac{{{m}_{1}}-{{m}_{2}}}{1+{{m}_{1}}{{m}_{2}}} \\right|$</p><p>the mod signifies that the angle we are considering is the acute angle and not the obtuse angle which is also formed when two lines intersect.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"213\" height=\"182\"></p><p><strong>Condition for two lines to be parallel&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{1}}={{\\text{m}}_{2}}$ i.e. the slope of two lines are equal.</p><p><strong>Note: </strong>Parallel lines never intersect, hence the angle between them is 0 .</p><p>i.e. $\\theta =0$ in this case.</p><p><strong>Condition for two lines to be perpendicular&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\Rightarrow {{\\text{m}}_{1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}}=-1$</p><p>i.e., the product of slopes of perpendicular lines, making an angle 90 with each other, is -1 .</p><p><strong>Tip: </strong>If the lines are given in general form i.e.</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; {{l}_{1}}:{{a}_{1}}x+{{b}_{1}}y+{{c}_{1}}=0 \\\\ {} &amp; {{l}_{2}}:{{a}_{2}}x+{{b}_{2}}y+{{c}_{2}}=0 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>then these lines are</p><p><strong>parallel: </strong>when $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{{{\\text{a}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{a}}_{2}}}=\\frac{{{\\text{b}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}_{2}}}\\ne \\frac{{{\\text{c}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{c}}_{2}}}$</p><p>or ${{\\text{a}}_{1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}_{2}}={{\\text{b}}_{1}}{{\\text{a}}_{2}}$</p><p><strong>perpendicular: </strong>when ${{a}_{1}}{{a}_{2}}+{{b}_{1}}{{b}_{2}}=0$</p><p>When the lines have been actually plotted tangent of any of the two angles between them can be written by the rule given below:</p><p>Mark the arrow from one line to the other in anticlockwise direction and take the slope of the line from which arrow starts as ${{\\text{m}}_{2}}$ and the slope of the line on which arrow goes as ${{\\text{m}}_{1}}$ as shown in the figure given alongside.</p><p>$\\text{tan}\\alpha =\\text{tan}\\left( {{\\theta }_{1}}-{{\\theta }_{2}} \\right)=\\frac{{{m}_{1}}-{{m}_{2}}}{1+{{m}_{1}}{{m}_{2}}}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"261\" height=\"188\"></p><p>Thus, when the lines have been actually plotted and their actual position are as given in the figure, then</p><p>$\\text{tan}\\alpha =\\frac{{{m}_{1}}-{{m}_{2}}}{1+{{m}_{1}}{{m}_{2}}},\\text{tan}\\beta =\\frac{{{m}_{2}}-{{m}_{1}}}{1+{{m}_{2}}{{m}_{1}}}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddc9c03b9dcaf1afecc1"
    }
  ],
